article.headline: E. Washington 110, Cal St.-Fullerton 100
article.story: CHENEY, Wash. (AP) -- Rodney Stuckey scored 27 points Monday night as Eastern Washington overcame an early deficit to outlast Cal State-Fullerton 110-100 in a nonconference game. In a contest that featured 14 lead changes, eight ties and 52 turnovers, Paul Butorac added 19 points and 10 rebounds for the Eagles (3-3), who rallied from 15 down in the first half to hand the Titans (4-1) their first loss of the season. With 6:45 left, Stuckey's driving layup capped a 10-0 run that gave EWU a 98-87 edge. Derek Risper, who finished with 18 points, scored six of the Eagles' next eight points and the Titans never got closer than six the rest of the way. In a fast-paced first half, the Titans used an 18-3 run, which included seven consecutive points from Bobby Brown, to forge a 38-23 lead with 8:45 left. EWU had committed nine turnovers to that point. But the Eagles rallied over the next six minutes, using back-to-back dunks from Risper to trigger a 24-7 burst that saw Eastern Washington take a 47-45 lead on Omar Krayem's 3-point play. Stuckey, who also had nine assists and five steals, led Eastern in scoring for the 33rd game in a row. Brandon Moore scored 13 points, Matt Penoncello 12 and Krayem 11 for the Eagles. Brown and Ray Reed each scored 20 points for the Titans. Scott Cutley had 19 points, Frank Robinson 16 and Marcus Crenshaw 11 for Cal State-Fullerton, which shot 53 percent from the floor compared with Eastern Washington's 61 percent.
